list.item:
Francisco Carrillo, 45 years; native of Cuba;
naturalized 1891; arrested at Remedios on February 24, 1895, upon a
gubernative order for not having inscribed himself in the register of
foreigners in any province of the island; confined in Cabanas fort;
released and deported to the United States May 29, 1895.

Juan Rodriguez Valdes, native of Cuba;
naturalized 1876; arrested at Puerto Principe April 5, 1895; released
April 6.

Justo Gener, 68 years; native of Cuba;
naturalized; arrested at Matanzas April 6; released April 9,
1895.

Mariano Rodriguez Zayas, native of Cuba;
arrested Habana September 17; released September 19, 1895; naturalized;
no charges.

Jose Martinez Mesa, 41 years; native of Cuba;
naturalized 1878; arrested at Habana September 17, 1895; released
September 19, 1895; no charges.

Joseph J. Trelles, native of Cuba;
naturalized; arrested at Matanzas December 24, 1895; released December
26, 1895; no charges.

Manuel M. (or W.) Amieva, 39 years; native of Cuba; naturalized 1878; arrested
at Matanzas December 24, 1895, as a suspect; released December 31, 1895;
no charges.

Louis Someillan, Sr., 58 years; born in Cuba,
naturalized Key West 1878; arrested January 17, 1896, at Habana;
released April 1, 1896; charge, aiding rebellion, sedition, etc.

Luis Martinez, arrested about March 1, 1896;
charged with treasonable correspondence; released April 13, 1896, on
$400 bail; naturalized 1873.

Frank J. Larrieu, native of Cuba; naturalized;
arrested at Cardenas May 15, 1896; case pending; charges not made
known.

Samuel T. Tolon, 45 years; native of Cuba;
naturalized 1878; arrested on board American steamer Seneca September 3, 1896; incomunicado twenty-two days;
charged with being a delegate to the Cuban Junta; released and deported
September 30, 1896; went to New York.

Joseph Austin Munoz, native of New Orleans;
arrested at Matanzas September 18, 1896; released September 19; claimed
that arrest was by mistake.

Ramon Rodriguez, native of Cuba; naturalized;
arrested September 20, 1896, upon requisition from governor of Matanzas;
had been in insurrection; surrendered and failed to report regularly;
sent to Cardena and released.

Esteben Cespedes (colored), born in Cuba;
naturalized Key West, 1891; arrested October 13, 1896, charged with
naniguismo (voodoo); expelled November 7, and went to Key West.

Fernando Pino Hernandez, 19 years (colored);
native of Key West; charged with naniguismo (voodoo); ordered to be
expelled December 30, 1896; will be sent to Key West.

Frank Agramont, and 62, Thos. Julio Sainz, arrested with arms in hand May, 1895;
charge, rebellion; to be tried for armed insurrection against the
Government; Santiago de Cuba.

frus:attachment.p:
Charles Michelson and Lorenzo
    Betancourt, correspondent and interpreter of New York Journal;
arrested February 25; confined in Morro Castle; released February 27, 1896;
charged with having communicated with insurgents by passing through Spanish
lines at Marianco, etc.
